Lean, rich and mildly gamey, our premium venison mince adds a beautiful depth of flavour
to this bolognese recipe. Seasoned with @dried Italian herbs{1/2%tsp}, @Worcester sauce{7.5%ml}
and @red wine stock paste{14%g}, Chef Lizzie's take on this classic pasta dish is a real
weeknight treat.

> To learn more about our venison supplier, make sure you head to our blog.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Add the @venison mince{200%g} and fry, breaking it up with a #wooden spoon{}, until
browned, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Pour the boiling water from your #kettle{} into a large #saucepan{} and return to the
boil with a pinch of @salt{} for the pasta.

Add the @wholewheat spaghetti{150%g} to the pan of boiling water.

Cook until al dente, around ~{11%minutes}, then drain in a #colander{}.

> 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of firmness
> left in the middle.

Mix the Italian herbs into the venison, then add the Worcester sauce, @tomato passata{1}
and @water{100%ml} (see ingredients for amount). Stir to dissolve the red wine stock.
Bring to the boil then reduce the heat and simmer until thick and tomatoey, ~{5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim and grate the @carrot{1} on a #coarse grater{} (no need to peel).

When the sauce is nice and rich, stir through the grated carrot.

Season to taste with salt, @pepper{} or a pinch of @?sugar{} (if you have any).

Stir the @baby spinach{125%g} through the bolognese a handful at a time to wilt it.

Toss through the drained pasta.

> Add a splash of water if you need to loosen up the sauce.

Serve the venison bolognese in #bowls{}, dig in and feel no guilt! ENJOY!